\begin_layout Section
Introduction 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Wedge 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The existing economics literature mainly focused on two-sided pricing to
 influence participation on the sides of the market.
 But many new marketplaces, such as Uber and Airbnb, are transactional matching
 marketplaces, in which the matching stage, which occurs after the stage
 of affiliation with the platform, matters a lot.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Wedge 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The new platforms, such as Uber and Airbnb, set the goal of bringing the
 idle capacities possessed by dispersed owners to the market where they
 can be efficiently traded.
 These platforms are dynamic matching marketplaces, that is characterized
 by the following features: the participants' preferences can be highly
 heterogenous, supply is limited in the short run, and the market runs continuou
sly.
 Therefore, bringing the owners to the platform is only half of the problem,
 because capacity may end up being under-utilized in the matching stage
 even when all participants are formally affiliated with the platform.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The platform operator has limited number of design tools at its disposal
 because it acts as an intermediary whose goal is to facilitate search and
 transactions, and often leaves price setting to the workers' discretion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Wedge 3.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
New platforms, such as Uber and Airbnb, were created with the aspiration
 of bringing to the market the idle capacities possessed by dispersed owners.
 These platforms facilitate search and transactions in order to match the
 capacities with potential buyers.
 Typically, in matching marketplaces, where heterogeneity is pronounced,
 the information provision is the key because it improves matching efficiency.
 Yet information availability increases workers' ability to screen potential
 buyers.
 The precise characterization and various consequences of this tradeoff
 constitute the theme of the present paper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First we show that in a matching marketplace with independent workers and
 stochastic buyer arrival, information availability creates undersirable
 competition among worker for better buyers which results in wasted capacity.
 Therefore, the intermeidary can improve matching by coarsening the information
 about buyers visible to the workers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Second, we characterize the optimal information disclosure policy as a function
 of worker cost heterogeneity and ...
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New platforms, such as Airbnb and Upwork, were created with the aspiration
 of bringing to the market the idle capacities possessed by dispersed owners.
 These platforms are matching marketplaces in the sense that both buyer
 and worker preferences are potentially highly heterogenous (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "DELS14,Fradkin2014,CFwp,Horton2015"

\end_inset

).
 Hence a platform's goal is to facilitate search and transactions between
 buyers and workers.
 In markets with pronounced heterogeneity, the information provision is
 the key because it improves matching efficiency (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HMS09"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 ?
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Yet information availability also gives service providers more control
 over the matching process, grants them more market power that may lead
 to inferior market outcomes.
 This creates a tradeoff between matching efficiency and rent-seeking.
 The precise characterization and various consequences of this tradeoff
 constitute the theme of the present paper.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I develop a model of a 
\emph on
dynamic peer-to-peer market 
\emph default
in which buyers arrive stochastically and request services from workers;
 a participating worker has heterogenous matching value across buyers (e.g.,
 heterogenous costs but posted price), his capacity is limited
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A distinguishing feature of a peer-to-peer marketplace relative to a retailer
 from the perspective of a consumer is the presence of heterogeneous sellers
 or goods with limited capacity or availability.
 (Fradkin 2016)
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and he is free to accept or reject buyer requests.
 Coarse segmentation of buyer tasks degrades matching quality for workers
 but also expands the set of equilibrium outcomes, namely it eliminates
 undesirable cream-skimming competition among workers.
 As a result, capacity utilization may increase.
 A combination of these two effects is that generically there exists a coarse
 segmentation of tasks on which the worker profits increase.
 Furthermore, buyers are also better off because higher capacity utilization
 implies shorter delays for buyers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dynamic peer-to-peer markets are increasingly relevant: there has been a
 10-fold growth in worker participation in online platforms over the last
 3 years (JP Morgan Chase, 2016).
 Nowadays 19% of the total US adult population has engaged in a sharing
 economy transaction (2015, PWC); Airbnb now lists more rooms than the three
 largest hotel chains combined (Fradkin); Uber has more drivers than taxi
 drivers in US.
 By 2025, online talent platforms could boost global GDP by $2.7 trillion
 (McKinsey, 2015).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many existing platforms have the problem of failed matches.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fradkin2014"

\end_inset

 finds that hosts on Airbnb reject proposals to transact by searchers 49%
 of the time.
 Using TaskRabbit data (from June 2010 to May 2014), 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CFwp"

\end_inset

 find that only 49% of posted tasks were successfully completed.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Horton2015"

\end_inset

 provides empirical evidence from online labor market UpWork that information
 asymmetry about workers capacity impacts the formation of matches in important
 ways.
 Part of the failed matches occurs due to workers' picking out buyers
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fradkin2014"

\end_inset

 reports that on Airbnb 20% of requests fail due to hosts' cream-skimming.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In this paper I study how the platform can use segmentation of buyer tasks
 to improve the utilization rates, where utilization is defined as the fraction
 of the aggregate service providers' capacity being used on average.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uber addressed the cream-skimming problem by limiting drivers rejection
 rate, and additionally hiding some passenger information from drivers,
 such as ride destination.
 Airbnb is also aware of the problem of worker low acceptance rate, and
 as a solution, introduced Instant Book feature.
 In my framework, a host who adopted Instant Book faces a single segment
 of guests so that he cannot discriminate among them.
 Airbnb is now working on fine tuning the Instant Book feature that would
 allow hosts to use a somewhat finer consumer segments.
 The natural question is how fine these segments should be allowed to be?
 TaskRabbit design defaults workers into accepting incoming tasks, so that
 rejecting tasks is harder because it requires additional actions.
 Moreover, TaskRabbit does not collect task details from customers before
 directing them to the search results.
 Offline markets which possess the same features as peer-to-peer platform
 are housing market, where the real-estate agency is the intermediary.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In firm-worker matching markets, individual firms may find it beneficial
 to engage in sequential rounds of interviews.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a peer-to-peer market, coarsening the segmentation of consumer tasks
 can improve utilization rates.
 Workers can discriminate only across segments, and thus coarser segments
 limit the extent of discrimination.
 For intuition, consider a simple static example: there is one worker, his
 hourly rate 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is posted in advance but the costs across potential tasks are heterogenous.
 The worker's optimal strategy is to accept all tasks with cost below 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and reject the tasks with cost above 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The intermediary can increase the worker's acceptance rate by grouping
 tasks right above 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with the tasks below 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 into one segment.
 The worker infers his expected cost for the segment.
 If the segment contains sufficiently many low-cost tasks, the average cost
 of a task from the segment is low enough, so that the worker is willing
 to accept a random task from the segment.
 Consequently, for any fixed price, the platform can increase the utilization
 rate by coarsening the segments of buyer tasks.
 This simple example, however, does not explain how segmentation influences
 the worker dynamic optimization problem and competition between workers,
 therefore we can't evaluate the equilibrium effect of segmentation and
 can't study implications for the welfare.
 Also in the example I assumed that the platform has complete information
 about the worker's cost, which would be a strong assumption in many application
s.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coarse segmentation may improve worker profits because information availability
 creates undesirable competition among workers for better buyers.
 Workers choose to keep their schedule open by ignoring low-return jobs
 in order to increase their individual chances of receiving high-return
 jobs.
 I call this behavior
\emph on
 dynamic cream-skimming.

\emph default
 Collectively, this behavior is sub-optimal for workers because all profitable
 jobs should be completed to maximize the joint profits.
 Dynamic cream-skimming results in wasted capacity and lowered worker profits.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, I characterize the optimal segmentation for the intermediary that
 wants to maximize total matches, as a function of worker cost heterogeneity
 and the distribution of workers' productivity.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 [Then I compare utilizaton-maximizing information policy with welfare-maximizin
g and profit-maximizing policies.
 I find ...
 ]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Paragraph
Minimal example of dynamic cream-skimming.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Suppose there are two identical workers.
 Every time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,2,...$
\end_inset

 one task arrives.
 Each task has profit 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=1/5$
\end_inset

 with equal probabilities.
 The new task is directed to one of the available workers chosen uniformly
 at random.
 If the worker accepts the task, he works on it the next period and does
 not receive new tasks.
 Each worker maximizes the all-time average profit; there is no discounting.
 I will compare two situations: in the first, the workers coordinate to
 maximize the joint profits, in the second, the workers play a blind Nash
 equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When the workers coordinate, it is optimal to accept every task.
 The expected per period profit for each worker is then 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{o}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{2}(1+\frac{1}{5})=.3$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now consider a Nash equilibrium in which workers do not observe each other
 states and act independently.
 I claim that a pair of strategies where each worker accepts only 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=1$
\end_inset

 is such an equilibrium.
 Indeed, in this equilibrium, expected per period profit for each worker
 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{*}=1/4$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose a worker receives a task with profit 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=1$
\end_inset

.
 If he accepts the task, he earns 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 over the course of two periods.
 If he rejects the task, he earns zero today and expects to earn 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{*}$
\end_inset

 tomorrow.
 Therefore the net payoff of accepting 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=1$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1-1/4=3/4>0$
\end_inset

, and so tasks 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=1$
\end_inset

 are accepted.
 Analogously, we find that the net payoff of accepting 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=1/5$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/5-1/4<0$
\end_inset

, and so tasks 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=1/5$
\end_inset

 are rejected.
 We conclude that the equilibrium outcome is not optimal for the workers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The platform can increase the workers' profits by not revealing the value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Then the expected profit of each task is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}(1+\frac{1}{5})=.6>0$
\end_inset

, and so every task is accepted.
 This attains the optimum.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This example shows that in peer-to-peer markets, independent service providers
 engage in self-defeating cream-skimming competition which results in lower
 profits compared to the case when workers coordinate.
 Fundamentally, this happens because jointly the workers are less capacity
 constrained than individually.
 In the example above, it is physically possible for workers to complete
 every buyer task (No Excess Demand assumption in the main model), and so
 collectively, the workers are not capacity constrained.
 Therefore, if the workers coordinate, they accept all profitable tasks
 and obtain the maximal profits.
 However, each individual worker 
\emph on
is
\emph default
 capacity constrained (in time), and thus has the option value of rejecting.
 Therefore, when workers act independently, they accept fewer tasks and
 make less profits.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Closely related intuition.
 workers wait to thicken the market in order to choose the best tasks.
 But this creates wasteful delays for buyers who are more time-sensitive.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

