\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Related-Literature"

\end_inset

Related Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My paper is adjacent to several literatures.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, vis-a-vis literature on pricing in two-sided platform (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RT06,Wey10"

\end_inset

), I make a point that in peer-to-peer markets, not only prices matter but
 also the matching mechanism.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, in Rochet and Tirole, a factor affecting elasticities on a
 given side is the size of the installed base of end-users on that side.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Second, vis-a-vis DAA literature which studies the centralized matching
 mechanism (kidney exchange, National Resident Matching Program), the markets
 I am interested in feature less control by the intermediary.
 The distinguishing feature of a peer-to-peer market is that a participant
 can typically decide whether to participate in a transaction or not after
 learning his counter-party.
 Intermediation in peer-to-peer platforms is therefore akin to regulation
 and anti-trust policies in industries.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The theory of two-sided matching generally assumes that agents know their
 true preferences over potential partners prior to engaging in a match —
 For a survey, see Roth and Sotomayor (1990)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Third, peer-to-peer market is not a bargaining network often found in health
 (cite Robin Lee).
 The intermediary imposes some basic structure on the marketplace, such
 as posted prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fourth, labor literature often assumes the black-box matching mechanism
 – matching function (Becker (1973); 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Shimer2000"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kircher2009"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 This does not allow to evaluate the policies that affect the matching mechanism
, such as information intermediation and minimal acceptance rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fifth, on the search side of the platform, the interaction of product differenti
ation and search costs have been studied by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AR99"

\end_inset

.
 They showed that when product differentiation increases, buyers search
 more.
 However, the total effect on price elasticity of demand is ambiguous.
 In the present paper the workers do not search but reject or accept incoming
 requests.
 Information coarsening decreases buyer task differentiation.
 On the one hand, workers are worse off because due to lack of information
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bla53"

\end_inset

).
 On the other hand, information coarsening softens cream-skimming competition
 among workers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been studies on dynamic matching markets and two-sided platforms
 in the literatures of economics and operations research.
 To the best of my knowledge, no prior work examined information disclosure
 in a dynamic mechanism design setting.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our main contribution is to the market design literature.
 A related paper that also studies dynamic matching is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AJM13"

\end_inset

.
 They show that waiting to thicken improves matching in kidney exchange
 because individual agents do not fully incorporate the benefits of waiting.
 I show there is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reversed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 effect: individual workers wait too long because they do not fully incorporate
 the lost value of rejection for buyers (or buyer waiting costs).
 Another related paper is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ALG16"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add description
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
look into Pathak's syllabus for more.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Effects of information disclosure in matching markets are multi-dimensional.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HMS09"

\end_inset

 shows that disclosing too much information can induce excessive costly
 signaling which overcomes the gains from improved matching.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mil10"

\end_inset

 shows that conflation increases prices of auctioned items if the items
 are identical and buyers have bidding costs.
 In his model, supply is fixed because the number of goods is pre-determined.
 Moreover, there is no cost of mismatch.
 In a closely related literature on targeting in advertising, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BB11"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AG10"

\end_inset

 evaluate the economic implications of improved targeting on market for
 advertising.
 In both 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BB11"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AG10"

\end_inset

, better targeting increases demand for advertising (efficiency effect).
 Higher demand pushes prices up.
 In both papers, supply effect of better targeting gives the same effect
 on prices but the underlying mechanisms are distinct.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BB11"

\end_inset

, better targeting leads to fewer advertisers in each outlet which lowers
 competition between advertisers and pushes prices down.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AG10"

\end_inset

, better targeting allows each outlet to better allocate scarce advertising
 space, so that more advertisers can be accommodated.
 This pushes prices down.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Search and matching also plays a large role in the economics of labor, housing,
 and household formation.
 Theoretical results in this literature such as Burdett, Shi and Wright
 (2001), Albrecht, Gautier and Vroman (2006), and Kircher (2009) show that
 markets where sellers have limited capacity, such as Airbnb, are inherently
 more frictional than markets with large firms.
 However, the main cause of inefficiency in these papers is congestion,
 which I show is relatively unimportant for Airbnb.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "DELS14"

\end_inset

 uses data from eBay to study ranking algorithms for differentiated products.
 In the framework of this paper, their Best Match algorithm is de-conflation
 of vertically differentiated goods.
 By making price a more important feature in search results, the goods are
 effectively grouped into price categories, so that it is now easier for
 buyers to find lower-priced goods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another closely related couple of papers is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HW15"

\end_inset

 and Hagiu and Wright (2016) that study the question of the intermediary's
 span of control in the platform it's running.
 There, the focus is on who, the platform or sellers, engages in complimentary
 activities (marketing, advertising).
 My explanation focuses on the matching mechanics and underscores the importance
 of buyer delays and supply heterogeneity in supply-demand fit.
 
\end_layout

